
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `hostnamectl` baraye didan va tagheer dadan name computer (hostname) estefade mishavad. Ba in dastoor mitoonid name static, pretty, va transient ra moratab konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `hostnamectl status`  --> ℹ️  Namayesh etela'at kamel dar morede hostname.
    🔹 `hostnamectl set-hostname [name]`  --> ✍️  Tagheer dadan name static computer be [name]. Baraye ejraye in dastoor shoma bayad dastrasi admin (root) dashte bashid.
    🔹 `hostnamectl set-hostname "[pretty name]"`  --> ✨  Tagheer dadan name "pretty" (ghabel fahm tar) computer.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ hostnamectl status

    🔹 Namayesh hameye etela'at marboot be hostname.

    $ sudo hostnamectl set-hostname mynewhostname

    🔹 Tagheer dadan name static computer be "mynewhostname".

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ hostnamectl

    🔹 Agar bedune gozine ejra konid, etela'at asasi hostname ra neshan midahad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `hostnamectl` command is used to view and modify the system's hostname.  It allows you to manage the static, pretty, and transient hostnames.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `hostnamectl status`  --> ℹ️  Display the complete hostname information.
    🔹 `hostnamectl set-hostname [name]`  --> ✍️  Set the static hostname to [name].  You need administrative (root) privileges to use this command.
    🔹 `hostnamectl set-hostname "[pretty name]"`  --> ✨  Set the "pretty" hostname (more user-friendly name).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ hostnamectl status

    🔹 Display all hostname-related information.

    $ sudo hostnamectl set-hostname mynewhostname

    🔹 Change the static hostname to "mynewhostname".

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ hostnamectl

    🔹  If executed without any options, it displays basic hostname information.
